  "summary": "Jeremy Claude confesses to his wife, Francis, that he has embezzled a trust fund and requires immediate funds to prevent the crime from being discovered. He expresses deep shame, fearing that Francis only married him for the stability and lack of scandal he once provided. Francis dismisses his sentimentality, asserting that she married him because she fell in love with his intellectual seriousness during a period when they were wealthy.\n\nRemaining calm and pragmatic, Francis notes that her own family has a history of covering up misdeeds involving her father and her cousins, Charles and Gerald. She maintains that while she is not perfectly virtuous, she is loyal. To resolve the financial crisis and prevent Jeremy from facing imprisonment, Francis suggests borrowing money from Rosalind, the widow of Gordon, whom she describes as \"the enigmatic Rosalind.\"\n\nJeremy hesitates, explaining that the funds are intended for Rosalind's living expenses. He reveals that under the law of intestacy of 1925, if Rosalind were to die, the money would pass to Gordon's nearest relatives. He identifies these potential heirs as himself, Leonel, Adela, and Morris's son, Rolly. As Francis realizes that the money would eventually pass to them through this inheritance, a chilling realization settles over the room.",
